<!-- 01 INTRO -->
<section class="section">
  <div class="container narrow">
    <p class="section-number">01, About Maytag washer repair</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">Maytag washers, Whirlpool platform, distinct positioning, four product families.</h2>

    <p>Maytag laundry is the brand's strongest category and one of the highest-volume washer brands in our 5-county SoCal service area. Maytag has been part of the Whirlpool Corporation family since 2006, which means engineering, parts, and supply chain run through Whirlpool's manufacturing infrastructure. Maytag washers and Whirlpool washers share platforms across most model generations, Bravos top-load mirrors Whirlpool Cabrio almost exactly, Maxima front-load mirrors Whirlpool Duet, Centennial mirrors entry-tier Whirlpool top-load. Same parts on our trucks, same diagnostic procedures.</p>

    <p>Two Maytag-specific service realities shape every diagnostic call. First, the <strong>"built to last" reputation is partially true</strong>: the Commercial-Technology models (MVWP washers) actually do use heavier-duty components and outlast equivalent Whirlpool-branded entry-tier units; the standard Bravos / Maxima / Centennial consumer models are typical mid-tier appliances mirroring their Whirlpool counterparts. We tell customers honestly which tier they have. Second, <strong>F-code error diagnostics on Maytag washers are identical to Whirlpool</strong>, F01, F02, F11, F26, and the rest follow the same diagnostic tree. A tech who knows Whirlpool washer codes already knows Maytag.</p>

    <p>This page covers Maytag washer repair across Bravos, Maxima, Centennial, and Commercial-Technology families. Every service call gets a $89 residential diagnostic (applied toward the repair when work is approved), OEM parts where we can, and an honest written quote before any work begins.</p>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- 02 COMMON PROBLEMS -->
<section class="section section-gray">
  <div class="container">
    <p class="section-number">02, Common Maytag washer problems</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">What goes wrong on Maytag washers, and how we diagnose it.</h2>

    <p class="lead">Five problem categories account for most Maytag washer service calls. Each has a typical year-window and a diagnostic order that gets to root cause efficiently.</p>

    <div class="appliance-grid">
      <div class="appliance-card">
        <h3>Won't start or stops mid-cycle</h3>
        <p>Bravos: lid lock / lid switch fault is the #1 cause (year 3-6 typical, F26 if displayed). Maxima: door lock / door boot tear preventing latch engagement. Diagnostic: visual lid/door inspection, switch ohms-out test, harness check. ~50% of mid-cycle stoppage traces here.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="appliance-card">
        <h3>Won't drain (F02)</h3>
        <p>Drain pump filter debris (coins, hair, lint) is the most common cause, clearing the filter is a 10-minute, no-parts fix on ~40% of these calls. Pump replacement when impeller has worn or motor has failed: $245-$385. Drain hose blockage or kink the rest.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="appliance-card">
        <h3>Won't spin or won't enter spin</h3>
        <p>Bravos: lid lock fault (~50%), shift actuator wear (~30%, year 5-8), drive belt slipping or broken (~15%), main control board (~5%). Maxima: door lock fault (~40%), drain incomplete from F02-class issue (~30%), control board (~20%), motor or MCU (~10%).</p>
      </div>
      <div class="appliance-card">
        <h3>Excessive vibration / unbalanced loads</h3>
        <p>Bravos (year 9+): suspension rod kit wear is the standard cause, basket starts walking. Replacement $245-$385. Maxima (year 8+): bearing wear or shock absorber wear; bearing replacement is the major repair ($585-$880 with seal as paired set).</p>
      </div>
      <div class="appliance-card">
        <h3>Leaking water</h3>
        <p>Bravos top-load: tub seal, water inlet valve, or drain pump seal failure. Maxima front-load: door boot tear (most common, year 8-10), drain pump seal, dispenser hose. Diagnostic: dye test or paper-towel trace to isolate origin during a fill cycle.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="appliance-card">
        <h3>Won't agitate or wash</h3>
        <p>Bravos: drive belt broken or shift actuator failed (motor runs but agitator/impeller doesn't move). Belt + actuator service $185-$345. Maxima: motor or MCU fault (less common); drum spins free but no wash cycle execution. Centennial: drive coupler failure year 6-9, common entry-tier wear item.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- 03 ERROR CODES -->
<section class="section">
  <div class="container narrow">
    <p class="section-number">03, Maytag washer error codes decoded</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">Identical to Whirlpool, same platform, same diagnostic tree.</h2>

    <p>Maytag washer error codes follow the Whirlpool F-series convention exactly because of the shared platform. The common ones we translate on every service visit:</p>

    <div class="error-table">
      <div class="error-row"><strong>F01</strong>, Main control board (CCU) communication or internal fault. Reset clears 10-15%; balance is CCU replacement.</div>
      <div class="error-row"><strong>F02 / F21</strong>, Long drain error. Drain time exceeded 8 minutes. Pump, hose, or filter clog.</div>
      <div class="error-row"><strong>F05</strong>, Water temperature sensor fault.</div>
      <div class="error-row"><strong>F06</strong>, Drive motor tachometer fault. Motor or MCU.</div>
      <div class="error-row"><strong>F07</strong>, Motor control unit (MCU) fault.</div>
      <div class="error-row"><strong>F09</strong>, Overflow / pressure sensor fault.</div>
      <div class="error-row"><strong>F11</strong>, Serial communication error between CCU and MCU. Wiring harness or one of the two boards.</div>
      <div class="error-row"><strong>F14</strong>, EEPROM error on CCU. Board replacement.</div>
      <div class="error-row"><strong>F20 / LF</strong>, Long fill error. Water supply, inlet valve, or pressure sensor.</div>
      <div class="error-row"><strong>F26</strong>, Door / lid switch error after 3 consecutive loads. Lid lock (Bravos), door lock (Maxima).</div>
      <div class="error-row"><strong>F28</strong>, Communication error CCU ↔ control panel.</div>
      <div class="error-row"><strong>Sud / Sd</strong>, Excess suds detected. Switch to HE detergent and reduce dose.</div>
      <div class="error-row"><strong>UL</strong>, Unbalanced load. Redistribute and restart; persistent UL = suspension rod or shock absorber wear.</div>
      <div class="error-row"><strong>Lid Lock / dL / dU</strong>, Lid lock or door lock fault. Bravos lid lock or Maxima door lock assembly.</div>
    </div>

    <p>Reset procedure for any Maytag washer error: kill the breaker for a full 10 minutes (longer than most appliances need to fully discharge filter capacitors). About 10-15% of error codes clear at this step at no parts cost. If the code returns, that's the diagnostic.</p>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- 04 MODELS -->
<section class="section section-gray">
  <div class="container">
    <p class="section-number">04, Maytag washer models we service most often</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">Bravos, Maxima, Centennial, Commercial-Technology families.</h2>

    <p class="lead">A representative sample of Maytag washer model families our techs service routinely.</p>

    <div class="model-grid">
      <div class="model-card">
        <h3>Bravos Top-Load (HE impeller)</h3>
        <p class="model-list">MVWB835DW · MVWX655DW · MVWB755DW · MVWB965HC · MVWB825JW · MVWX700XW</p>
        <p>Bravos HE top-load family. MVWB-series. Lid lock and suspension rod dominate service mix. Mirrors Whirlpool Cabrio service tree exactly.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="model-card">
        <h3>Maxima Front-Load</h3>
        <p class="model-list">MHW8630HW · MHW6630HW · MHW5630HW · MHW8200FC · MHW3505FW · MHW7000XG</p>
        <p>Maxima front-load family. MHW-series. Drain pump, door boot, bearing service. Year 8-12 bearing typical for retention. Mirrors Whirlpool Duet.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="model-card">
        <h3>Centennial Entry-Tier Top-Load</h3>
        <p class="model-list">MVWC465HW · MVWC565FW · MVWC400XW · MVWC555DW · MVWC565JW</p>
        <p>Entry-tier Centennial. Simpler architecture, drive-belt transmission, more mechanical-feeling. Most reliable Maytag washer through year 10+ because fewer electronic components.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="model-card">
        <h3>Commercial-Technology Premium</h3>
        <p class="model-list">MVWP575GW · MVWP576KW · MVWP585GW · MVWP586GW</p>
        <p>Heavier-duty consumer-marketed models. MVWP washers use commercial-grade components (heavier motor, tougher transmission). Year 12-15 typical service life with normal maintenance, the "built to last" claim is closer to true here.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="model-card">
        <h3>Legacy Direct-Drive Top-Load</h3>
        <p class="model-list">MVWX500XW · MAH9700AWW · MAH8700AWW · MAH4000AWW</p>
        <p>Pre-Bravos direct-drive top-loaders still in heavy service in older homes. Mechanical-feeling controls, agitator-based wash. Drive coupler and motor coupling dominate service tree on these.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="model-card">
        <h3>Maytag Commercial Laundry</h3>
        <p class="model-list">MFR50PD · MAH22PD · MAH22PR · MAT12PD</p>
        <p>True commercial Maytag for laundromats, multi-family housing, on-premise laundry. Different service tree, coin / card systems, heavier-duty motors, longer programming. Specialty work; we dispatch commercial-trained techs.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

